 self-evaluation and to root out anthropomorphic assumptions embedded in its own methodology. Calling for a reexamination of beliefs central to the Western philosophical tradition, this book shifts previously marginalized environmental concerns to the forefront and blazes a trail for a new collaboration between phenomenologists and ecologically-minded theorists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEcologyxPhilosophy. 0aEnvironmentalismxPhilosophy. 0aPhenomenology. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Charles S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Charles S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCasey, Edward S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiehm, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmbree, Lester, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaver, Irene J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohák, Erazim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanger, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLlewelyn, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarietta, Don E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToadvine, Ted, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToadvine, Ted, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWood, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZimmerman, Michael E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737